### Description

We can react to changes in a route parameter using code like this:
```
// WORKS
  idA = 0;
  ngOnInit(): void {
    this.route.params.subscribe((data) => {
      this.idA = data['id'];
    });
  }
```
This code still works. But when using the new `Input` property for route parameters, there is no notification when the route parameter changes. The Input property setter does not execute and the ngOnChanges does not respond to a change.
```
  // Using setter
  // DOES NOT WORK
  _idB = '0';
  @Input()
  get idB(): string {
    return this._idB;
  }
  set idB(value: string) {
    this._idB = value;
    console.log(this.idB);
  }

  // Using NgOnChanges
  // DOES NOT WORK
  idC = 0;
  ngOnChanges(changes: SimpleChanges) {
    this.idC = Number(changes.id.currentValue);
    console.log(changes);
  }

```
The expectation is that when using the `Input` property for the route parameters, it should modify the property when the route parameter changes.

